snippet.textDisplay:
there are TWO problems that i have with this video
1) Ramen is the romaji of the word 拉麺 when written as kanji, which originated as a Chinese word and can also be written as ラーメン in Katakana, a set of japanese characters used when handling a foreign word, and is pronounced La-men, instead of Ra-men.
ramen is a butcherised pronunciation of the japanese word using english when handling the R sound where Americans take the R sound as literal R, whereas in japanese, should be somewhere between R and L but closer to L than R. since i is not an english word or any language that has roman origins to start with, we should respect the original language and pronounce it as it should be, not as you like.
2) it literally means pulled noodles, not roughly translated to pull noodles
snippet.textOriginal:
there are TWO problems that i have with this video
1) Ramen is the romaji of the word 拉麺 when written as kanji, which originated as a Chinese word and can also be written as ラーメン in Katakana, a set of japanese characters used when handling a foreign word, and is pronounced La-men, instead of Ra-men.
*ramen* is a butcherised pronunciation of the japanese word using english when handling the R sound where Americans take the R sound as literal R, whereas in japanese, should be somewhere between R and L but closer to L than R. since i is not an english word or any language that has roman origins to start with, we should respect the original language and pronounce it as it should be, not as you like.
2) it *literally means* pulled noodles, *not roughly translated* to pull noodles
